1. Task - Choose one or more suitable web API¶¶

I have used Zomato API for this assignment.

  • Zomato API is used using an API key to analyze and compare restaurants of Dublin. The API key is 53731a7e2eb6195ed6a58eaf0e4f6b31
  • Below are the limitation of using this API
    • We can make only up to 1000 calls/day
    • We can get up to 100 restaurants details by changing the 'start' and 'count' parameters with the maximum value of count being 20. To overcome this limitation, I have fetched data on the basis of all the cuisines available in dublin. By doing so, I was able to get data for 1927 unique resturants
    • In the basic API plan, we can get only 5 reviews for each restaurants. Also, these reviews are not complete, we only get first 150 characters of each review. I have done the analysis using this available data. I have 5463 reviews in the dataset
  • I have used Web Scrapping using BeautifulSoup to fetch highlights of each restaurant. Highlights refer to the services which the restuarant provide like Indoor Seating, Takeaway, Breakfast etc.

I am analyzing data only for Dublin whose city_id is 91 in Zomato Database. I have used longitude(-6.248889) and latitude(53.333056) value to find the id

Fetching Data for Restaurants¶

We can get up to 100 restaurants details by changing the 'start' and 'count' parameters with the maximum value of count being 20. To overcome this limitation, I have fetched the data on the basis of all the 68 cuisines available in Dublin. By doing so, I was able to get data for 1927 unique resturants Also for each cuisines, we can get maximum 100 restaurants. So I am running the loop 5 times and at each iteration, I am changing the value of start to fetch 20 new records from new starting point. If there are less restaurants for a cuisine, in that case I am checking the results value. If there are no more restaurants for that cuisine, then I am breaking out of the loop. This will prevent unnecessary API calls.
Please Note
In the below code, we are saving all the JSON files in restaurants folder. If you run the below command, all the files will be saved in that location. For the further analysis please use restaurants_data folder, as that will have all the data which was collected on various days.

In [1419]:
for cuisine_id in cuisines_dataset['cuisine_id']:
    count =0
    start=0
    while count < 5:
        if api_count <= 1000:
            link='https://developers.zomato.com/api/v2.1/search?start=%d&count=20&lat=53.333056&lon=-6.248889&cuisines=%d' % (start,cuisine_id)
            restro_results=requests.get(link,headers={'Accept':'application/json','user-key':'53731a7e2eb6195ed6a58eaf0e4f6b31'})
            api_count=api_count+1 
            restro_json=restro_results.json()
            results = restro_json['results_shown']
            if(results == 0):
                break;
            else:
                try:
                    file_name='%d_%d.json'% (cuisine_id,count)
                    file_name=os.path.join(os.getcwd(),'restaurants',file_name)
                    file = open(file_name, "w")
                    file.write(restro_results.text)
                    file.close()
                    start = start+20
                    count += 1
                except Exception as h:
                    print("Cannot write to file \nError:"+str(h))      
        else:
            print("Number of API Request exceeded. Please try next day by resetting api_count variable to zero")  
            break; #this will come out of while loop
           
    if(api_count > 1000):
        print("Number of API Request exceeded. Please try next day by resetting api_count variable to zero")  
        break #this is coming out of for loop

Fetching More Info data for each Restaurant using Web Scrapping¶

I have used BeautifulSoup to scrap the data for each restuarant. I have got the URL for each restaurant from the search API which is used to fetch data for restaurants. I have created a dataframe where we have restaurant ID along with it's highlight and whether it's Present ot Not Present. Red cross means "Not Present" and Blue Tick means "Present"

Please Note that this will take around 15-20 mins to run as we have around 2000 restaurants and we need to do scrapping for each one of them

In [1913]:
highlight=[]
count=0;
process_count=100;
#Iterating through the restaurants_dataset
for index, row in restaurants_dataset.iterrows():
    restaurant_id=row["restaurant_id"]
    url=row["url"]
    headers = {'User-Agent': 'Mozilla/5.0 (Macintosh; Intel Mac OS X 10_11_6) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/61.0.3163.100 Safari/537.36'}
    response = requests.get(url,headers=headers)
    content = response.content
    soup = BeautifulSoup(content,"html.parser")
    rest_highlights = soup.find_all("div",attrs={"class": "res-info-highlights"})
    #To iterate through each highlight or more info of a particular restaurant
    for EachHighlight in rest_highlights[0].select('div[class*="clearfix mb5"]'):
        iconText=EachHighlight.find("i")
        if 'red' in iconText['class']:
            icon="Not Present"
        elif 'green' in iconText['class']:
            icon="Present"
        text=EachHighlight.find("div").text
        highlight.append([restaurant_id,text,icon])  
    count=count+1
    if (count == process_count):
        text="Web Scrapping done for %d restaurants"%(count)
        print(text)
        process_count = process_count+100

#Folder Location where all the JSON files are stored
path_to_json = './reviews_data/'
#Finding only the JSON files
json_files = [pos_json for pos_json in os.listdir(path_to_json) if pos_json.endswith('.json')]

reviews_list = []
for index, js in enumerate(json_files):
    with open(os.path.join(path_to_json, js)) as json_file:
        #Reading the JSON file
        reviews = json.load(json_file)
        reviews = reviews['user_reviews']
        #Fetching the restaurant_id from the file name
        restaurant_id=js[:-5]
        for review in reviews:
            reviews_list.append([restaurant_id,review['review']['rating'],review['review']['review_text'],

10. Performing Sentiment Analysis of the reviews and creating new columns to store the sentiment result in merged review dataset

I am using VADER (Valence Aware Dictionary and sEntiment Reasoner) sentiment analysis. It is a lexicon and rule-based sentiment analysis tool that is specifically attuned to sentiments expressed in social media. It gives us positive, negative, neutral and compound score for each review. The Compound score is a metric that calculates the sum of all the lexicon ratings which have been normalized between -1 and +1. I am using this score, to find the sentiment of the review. If the compound score >=0.05, it's a positive sentiment. If the compound score >-0.05 and compound score <0.05, then it's a neutral sentiment. And if compound score <=-0.05, it's a negative sentiment. I have created a new column to store the sentiment value according to above criterion.

In [65]:
analyzer = SentimentIntensityAnalyzer()
#Storing four type of scores
compound=[]
neg=[]
neu=[]
pos=[]
sentiment=[]
for index, row in restaurants_review_merged_df.iterrows():
    sentence=str(row['review_text']) 
    #below command performs the sentiment analysis and produces the positive, negative, neutral and compund score for 
    #each review
    vs = analyzer.polarity_scores(sentence)
    compound.append(vs['compound'])
    neg.append(vs['neg'])
    neu.append(vs['neu'])
    pos.append(vs['pos'])
    #On the basis of compound score, we can classify the review as positive, negative or neutral
    if(vs['compound'] >= 0.05):
        sentiment.append('Positive')
    elif( (vs['compound'] > -0.05) & (vs['compound'] < 0.05 )):
        sentiment.append('Neutral')
    elif(vs['compound'] <= -0.05):
        sentiment.append('Negative')

#creating new column in restaurants_review_merged_df to store the result for anlaysis        
restaurants_review_merged_df['compound'] = compound
restaurants_review_merged_df['neg'] = neg
restaurants_review_merged_df['neu'] = neu
restaurants_review_merged_df['pos'] = pos
restaurants_review_merged_df['sentiment'] = sentiment

5.18 Distribution of Aggregate Rating According to Sentiments¶

In [100]:
x=restaurants_review_merged_df.sentiment
y=restaurants_review_merged_df.aggregate_rating.astype(float)
sns.set_style("whitegrid")
my_pal = {"Positive": "#009900", "Negative": "#b30000", "Neutral":"#e6e600"}
plt.subplots(figsize=(10,7))
ax = sns.boxplot(x=x, y=y,palette=my_pal)
ax.set_title('Distribution of Aggregate Rating According to Sentiments',fontsize=20)
ax.set_ylabel('Aggregate Rating',fontsize=14)
ax.set_xlabel('Sentiments',fontsize=14)
plt.show()

Graph Insight
We can see from the above graph that most of the positive reviews have aggreagte rating between 3.2 -3.8. Maximum rating for positive review is around 4.8 and minimum as 2.1. For negative reviews, fifty percent of the aggreagte rating is between 2.8- 3.6. For Neutral reviews, maximum ratings are between 3.1 - 3.7. This result can be because of the limitation of Zomato API. We only get first 150 charaters of the review. If we get full review, then we can get more accurate data. But in general we can see that Positive Review have better aggregate rating than Negative reviews

Insights about Dublin restaurants from the Zomato dataset

  • Popular Restaurants, Cuisines and Localities
    • Most popular restaurants in Dublin are Eddie Rocket, Subway and McDonald's (Graph 2)
    • Most popular cuisines in Dublin are Asian, Cafe, Fast Food, Irish and Chinese (Graph 3)
    • South City West, South City East, North City, Temple Bar and Ballsbridge have maximum number of restaurants in Dublin (Graph 5)
  • Rating of Restaurants
    • People have rated majority restaurants as “Average” or "Good". Only few restaurants have been rated as "Excellent". Also there are many restaurants that have not been rated (Graph 1)
    • There are only few restaurants, which have “Excellent” rating, and most of then are in Temple Bar and South City West Region. All other regions have most of the rating as “Average” or “Good”. So we can say that Temple Bar and South City West Region has best restaurants in Dublin (Graph 7)
    • The most sold cuisine is Asian cuisine but the highly rated cuisine is Irish cuisine (Graph 8)
  • Average Cost For Two
    • Most of the restaurants in Dublin have average cost for two, between 15 and 40 euro. There are very few restaurants, which have average cost for two more than 80 euro. Also there are very few restaurants with average cost for two less than 10 euro (Graph 4
    • We saw that there is no relation between average cost for two and aggregate Rating. Most of the restaurants have average cost for two between 15 and 40 euro. And in that range we have all kind of ratings (Graph 9)
  • Analysis of Highlights/ Facilities Available in Restaurants
    • Most of the restaurants in Dublin have facilities like Indoor Seating, Takeaway facility, Wi-Fi, Bar and Breakfast option (Graph 10)
    • South City West, South City East, North City, Temple Bar and Ballsbridge areas have maximum restaurants that provide Takeaway, Nightlife and Breakfast option (Graph 11, 12, 13)
    • We saw that restaurants with above average rating have Indoor Seating, Wi-Fi, Full Bar Available, Takeaway Available and Lunch Menu options (Table 14)
    • We saw that restaurants with Poor rating don’t have takeaway option and alcohol availability. Restaurants that have Average and above rating have these facilities. So these options plays an important role in determining the rating (Table 15)
  • Sentiment Analysis of Reviews
    • Please Note that Zomato API has a restriction that only 5 reviews can be fetched for a particular restaurant. And also we get only first 150 characters of each review. So below analysis may be impacted because of it.
    • By performing sentiment analysis on the reviews, we saw that majority of the reviews are positive. And only few restaurants have negative or neutral review. This finding was also seen in Graph 1 where we were analysing the rating of users. We saw that most of the users have rated restaurants as either “Average” or “Good”, which means positive reviews. Only few restaurants have been rated as “Poor”. (Graph 16)
    • We have also analysed reviews on the basis of top ten popular localities. Reviews are mostly positive there. In South City West, we have few restaurants with neutral or negative reviews. Otherwise mostly have positive review. This finding was also seen while we were analysing rating on the basis of localities (Graph 7). (Graph 17)
    • We also analysed the relation between sentiment of reviews and aggregate rating. From the graph we saw that most of the positive reviews have aggregate rating between 3.2 -3.8. For negative reviews, fifty percent of the aggregate rating is between 2.8- 3.6. For Neutral reviews, maximum ratings are between 3.1 - 3.7. If we get full reviews, then we can get more accurate data. But in general we can see that Positive Review have better aggregate rating than Negative reviews (Graph 18)
    • We also analysed the sentiments of reviews on the basis of Foodie Level of users. All Foodie Level of users gives majority of positive reviews. Foodie and Big Foodie gives more negative reviews than Connoisseur or Super Foodie users (Graph 19)
